  "prompt": "Why is the RuPay card not accepted in other countries?",
  "response": "RuPay cards have limited international acceptance primarily due to the following reasons:\n\n1. Domestic network: RuPay is primarily an Indian domestic payment network developed by the National Payments Corporation of India (NPCI).\n\n2. Limited global infrastructure: Unlike Visa, Mastercard, or American Express, RuPay lacks extensive international payment infrastructure.\n\n3. Fewer international tie-ups: The card network has fewer agreements with international banks and merchants compared to global payment networks.\n\n4. Focus on domestic market: RuPay was initially designed to serve the Indian market and reduce dependence on international card networks.\n\n5. Relatively new network: Launched in 2012, RuPay is still developing its international presence and acceptance.\n\nWhile RuPay is working to expand its international reach, currently, the card is mostly accepted within India. For international transactions, users typically need to use Visa, Mastercard, or other global payment networks.\n\nHowever, RuPay has been gradually expanding its international acceptance, and some progress has been made in countries like Bhutan and the UAE.",
